1
00:00:01,041 --> 00:00:02,401
(CLOCK TICKING)

2
00:00:02,561 --> 00:00:04,481
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

3
00:00:16,201 --> 00:00:17,561
(MECHANICAL WHIRRING, SQUEAKS)

4
00:01:07,521 --> 00:01:09,201
(CHIMING)

5
00:01:16,641 --> 00:01:18,201
(GUITAR RIFFS)

6
00:01:22,201 --> 00:01:23,321
(CLEARS THROAT)

7
00:01:27,401 --> 00:01:28,641
(FEEDBACK)

8
00:01:29,201 --> 00:01:30,561
(GUITAR CRACKLING)

9
00:01:30,921 --> 00:01:32,961
(ELECTRONIC WHIRRING)

10
00:01:36,201 --> 00:01:38,321
-Potts?
-Yeah.

11
00:01:38,881 --> 00:01:39,881
Bill Potts?

12
00:01:40,401 --> 00:01:41,401
You wanted to see me?

13
00:01:42,041 --> 00:01:44,161
You're not a student of this university?

14
00:01:44,641 --> 00:01:45,841
No, I work in the canteen.

15
00:01:45,921 --> 00:01:48,201
-Yeah, but you come to my lectures.
-No, I don't.

16
00:01:48,441 --> 00:01:49,641
(NERVOUSLY) I never do that.

17
00:01:49,921 --> 00:01:50,921
I've seen you.

18
00:01:51,601 --> 00:01:54,601
Love your lectures,
they're totally awesome.

19
00:01:54,681 --> 00:01:56,561
Why did you come to my lectures,
when you're not a student?

20
00:01:56,681 --> 00:01:58,521
Okay, so my first day here,

21
00:01:58,641 --> 00:02:00,721
in the canteen, I was on chips.
There was this girl,

22
00:02:00,881 --> 00:02:02,401
student, beautiful,

23
00:02:02,481 --> 00:02:05,161
like a model,
only with talking and thinking.

24
00:02:05,441 --> 00:02:07,001
She looked at you and you perved.

25
00:02:07,281 --> 00:02:09,681
Every time. Automatic like physics,

26
00:02:09,841 --> 00:02:11,601
eye contact, perversion.

27
00:02:11,921 --> 00:02:13,601
So, I gave her extra chips.

28
00:02:13,681 --> 00:02:15,521
Every time, extra chips.

29
00:02:15,601 --> 00:02:17,161
Like a reward, for perversion.

30
00:02:17,241 --> 00:02:20,001
Every day, got myself on chips,
rewarded her.

31
00:02:20,081 --> 00:02:22,241
Then finally, finally, she looked at me,

32
00:02:23,281 --> 00:02:27,001
like she didn't notice that I actually
noticed all the extra chips.

33
00:02:27,081 --> 00:02:28,081
Do you know what I realised?

34
00:02:28,681 --> 00:02:29,681
She was fat.

35
00:02:31,281 --> 00:02:32,281
I had fatted her.

36
00:02:34,481 --> 00:02:35,761
That's life, isn't it?

37
00:02:35,841 --> 00:02:37,441
Beauty or chips? I like chips.

38
00:02:37,601 --> 00:02:39,921
So does she, so... That's okay.

39
00:02:40,681 --> 00:02:44,561
And how does that in any way explain
why you keep coming to my lectures?

40
00:02:45,121 --> 00:02:46,801
Yeah, it doesn't really, does it?

41
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:48,841
I was hoping something would develop.

42
00:02:49,041 --> 00:02:50,041
What's that?

43
00:02:51,081 --> 00:02:52,321
A police telephone box?

44
00:02:53,921 --> 00:02:55,921
-Yeah.
-Did you build it from a kit?

45
00:02:56,721 --> 00:02:58,841
-No, it came like that.
-Then, how did you get it in here?

46
00:02:59,121 --> 00:03:00,881
The door is too small,
and so are the windows.

47
00:03:01,121 --> 00:03:02,921
I had the window and a part of the wall

48
00:03:03,041 --> 00:03:04,201
taken out, and it was lifted in.

49
00:03:04,361 --> 00:03:05,601
-Oh, with a crane?
-Yeah.

50
00:03:05,841 --> 00:03:07,881
With a crane.

51
00:03:08,281 --> 00:03:10,841
It's heavier than it looks.
Why do you keep coming to my lectures?

52
00:03:11,241 --> 00:03:12,241
Because I like them.

53
00:03:12,681 --> 00:03:14,881
Everybody likes them, they're amazing.

54
00:03:16,321 --> 00:03:18,161
-Why me?
-Why you, what?

55
00:03:18,241 --> 00:03:19,921
Well, plenty of people come
to your lectures

56
00:03:20,001 --> 00:03:21,401
that aren't supposed to,
why pick on me?

57
00:03:21,521 --> 00:03:23,001
Well, I noticed you.

58
00:03:23,081 --> 00:03:24,081
BILL: Yeah, but why?

59
00:03:26,561 --> 00:03:29,041
Well, most people, when they don't
understand something, they frown.

60
00:03:29,121 --> 00:03:30,361
You...

61
00:03:31,441 --> 00:03:32,441
Smile.

62
00:03:35,161 --> 00:03:36,161
Tell you what I don't understand.

63
00:03:36,801 --> 00:03:38,601
You've been lecturing here a long time,

64
00:03:39,001 --> 00:03:41,041
about 50 years, some people say.

65
00:03:41,281 --> 00:03:43,241
-My B-Line in the office says over 70.
-Yeah,

66
00:03:43,641 --> 00:03:45,401
and you're thinking,
"Well, he doesn't look old enough.”

67
00:03:45,481 --> 00:03:48,241
No, I'm wondering what you're
supposed to be lecturing on?

68
00:03:48,681 --> 00:03:51,281
It's like the university let
you do whatever you like.

69
00:03:51,721 --> 00:03:54,281
One time, you were going to give
a lecture on quantum physics,

70
00:03:54,361 --> 00:03:55,361
you talked about poetry.

71
00:03:55,441 --> 00:03:57,041
Poetry, physics, same thing.

72
00:03:57,201 --> 00:03:58,641
How is it the same?

73
00:03:58,721 --> 00:04:00,961
Because of the rhymes,
what are you doing at this university?

74
00:04:01,041 --> 00:04:02,041
I always wanted to come here.

75
00:04:02,121 --> 00:04:03,761
Yeah, to serve chips?

76
00:04:05,401 --> 00:04:07,521
So anyway, am I nearly done?

77
00:04:07,761 --> 00:04:08,761
Do you wanna be?

78
00:04:09,121 --> 00:04:10,121
See ya.

79
00:04:12,721 --> 00:04:14,681
You ever get less
than a first and it's over.

80
00:04:15,561 --> 00:04:16,841
-You what?
-A first,

81
00:04:17,801 --> 00:04:18,801
every time,

82
00:04:18,921 --> 00:04:19,961
or I stop immediately.

83
00:04:20,081 --> 00:04:21,121
Stop what?

84
00:04:21,201 --> 00:04:22,881
Being your personal tutor.

85
00:04:24,561 --> 00:04:26,401
But I'm not a student.

86
00:04:27,001 --> 00:04:30,001
I'm not a part of the university,
I never even applied.

87
00:04:30,361 --> 00:04:31,641
We'll sort all of that out later.

88
00:04:31,801 --> 00:04:33,401
You kinda have to sort that out earlier.

89
00:04:33,721 --> 00:04:35,521
Leave it with me,
I'm assuming that it's a "yes"?

90
00:04:37,201 --> 00:04:38,241
Yes.

91
00:04:38,321 --> 00:04:40,481
I'll see you at 6:00 p.m. every weekday.

92
00:04:40,601 --> 00:04:42,881
I don't care who is dying,
never, ever be late.

93
00:04:42,961 --> 00:04:44,321
I'm very particular about time.

94
00:04:47,681 --> 00:04:48,681
Oh...

95
00:04:50,561 --> 00:04:52,761
People just call you "The Doctor”.

96
00:04:53,601 --> 00:04:54,601
What do I call you?

97
00:04:55,361 --> 00:04:56,441
The Doctor.

98
00:04:56,681 --> 00:04:58,361
But Doctor's not a name.

99
00:04:58,641 --> 00:05:00,681
I can't just call you Doctor.

100
00:05:02,321 --> 00:05:03,321
Doctor what?

101
00:05:04,961 --> 00:05:06,961
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

102
00:05:41,921 --> 00:05:43,081
(ALARM BUZZING)

103
00:05:48,041 --> 00:05:49,761
Time. Time doesn't pass.

104
00:05:50,481 --> 00:05:52,561
The passage of time is an illusion,

105
00:05:52,641 --> 00:05:54,401
and life is the magician,

106
00:05:56,521 --> 00:06:00,081
because life only lets you
see one day at a time.

107
00:06:05,241 --> 00:06:06,721
You remember being alive yesterday,

108
00:06:06,801 --> 00:06:08,561
you hope you're going
to be alive tomorrow.

109
00:06:08,681 --> 00:06:10,761
So, it feels like you're travelling

110
00:06:11,001 --> 00:06:14,001
one to the other,
but nobody is moving anywhere.

111
00:06:15,201 --> 00:06:17,041
-DOCTOR: Movies don't really move.
-(CHURCH BELL SOUNDS)

112
00:06:17,961 --> 00:06:20,481
They're just pictures,
lots and lots of pictures.

113
00:06:20,561 --> 00:06:23,881
All of them still, none of them moving,
just frozen moments.

114
00:06:24,281 --> 00:06:26,481
-(BELL RINGS)
-(CAMERAS CLICKING)

115
00:06:27,641 --> 00:06:31,401
DOCTOR: If you experience those
pictures one after the other...

116
00:06:31,601 --> 00:06:33,361
-(BELL RINGS)
-...then everything comes alive.

117
00:06:37,881 --> 00:06:38,881
Am I on time?

118
00:06:39,001 --> 00:06:40,761
That's a very big question.

119
00:06:47,321 --> 00:06:49,161
BILL: You know, you're my foster mum,

120
00:06:49,921 --> 00:06:51,441
he's like my foster tutor.

121
00:06:51,721 --> 00:06:53,761
Am I gonna have to break
every bone in his body?

122
00:06:54,401 --> 00:06:55,681
It's not like that.

123
00:06:55,961 --> 00:06:57,361
You need to keep your eye on men.

124
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:02,081
(WHISPERING) Men aren't where
I keep my eye actually.

125
00:07:02,161 --> 00:07:04,441
Imagine if time all happened at once...

126
00:07:04,641 --> 00:07:06,081
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

127
00:07:06,681 --> 00:07:09,121
...every moment of your life

128
00:07:09,361 --> 00:07:11,081
laid out around you

129
00:07:12,881 --> 00:07:14,001
like a city.

130
00:07:14,081 --> 00:07:16,801
Streets full of buildings, made of days.

131
00:07:16,921 --> 00:07:20,081
The day you were born, the day you die,

132
00:07:20,241 --> 00:07:21,761
the day you fall in love,

133
00:07:21,921 --> 00:07:24,481
the day that love ends. A whole city,

134
00:07:24,681 --> 00:07:27,881
built from triumph and heartbreak

135
00:07:27,961 --> 00:07:31,161
and boredom and laughter
and cutting your toenails,

136
00:07:31,241 --> 00:07:33,561
it's the best place you'll ever be.

137
00:07:33,641 --> 00:07:35,241
(INDISTINCT CHATTER AND LAUGHTER)

138
00:07:36,681 --> 00:07:40,081
DOCTOR: 7ime is a structure,
relative to ourselves.

139
00:07:45,401 --> 00:07:46,401
I'll get him in.

140
00:07:46,681 --> 00:07:49,481
DOCTOR: Time is the space
made by our lives,

141
00:07:51,201 --> 00:07:54,321
where we stand together forever.

142
00:07:55,521 --> 00:07:56,521
Time

143
00:07:56,681 --> 00:07:59,041
and relative dimension

144
00:08:00,761 --> 00:08:01,761
in

145
00:08:03,401 --> 00:08:04,441
space.

146
00:08:05,761 --> 00:08:07,361
It means life.

147
00:08:07,801 --> 00:08:09,121
(ALARM BUZZING)

148
00:08:10,521 --> 00:08:11,521
-Chips, yeah?
-Please.

149
00:08:31,041 --> 00:08:32,441
NARDOLE: Huh, oh!

150
00:09:04,881 --> 00:09:07,601
NARDOLE: So, you're tutoring her and...

151
00:09:07,681 --> 00:09:09,081
DOCTOR: Mmm-hmm, yes I am.

152
00:09:10,321 --> 00:09:12,281
-NARDOLE: Why?
-DOCTOR: Why not?

153
00:09:12,361 --> 00:09:14,201
NARDOLE: You're not supposed
to be get involved.

154
00:09:15,561 --> 00:09:17,161
What are you teaching her anyway?

155
00:09:17,321 --> 00:09:18,321
DOCTOR: Everything.

156
00:09:18,801 --> 00:09:20,841
NARDOLE: How can you teach
anyone everything?

157
00:09:20,921 --> 00:09:23,521
-DOCTOR: Because everything rhymes.
-NARDOLE: Oh.

158
00:09:23,681 --> 00:09:24,921
(WHIRRING)

159
00:09:25,001 --> 00:09:27,161
(CONVERSING INDISTINCTLY)

160
00:09:29,361 --> 00:09:30,361
(ELECTRONIC SOUNDS)

161
00:09:35,401 --> 00:09:37,001
-NARDOLE: Rotate it.
-DOCTOR: Ah.

162
00:09:41,601 --> 00:09:43,081
-(GASPS)
-(CLANGING)

163
00:09:43,721 --> 00:09:45,041
(WHIRRING STOPS)

164
00:09:50,041 --> 00:09:52,241
The door upstairs,
how did you set the security?

165
00:09:52,881 --> 00:09:53,881
Friends only.

166
00:09:57,641 --> 00:09:59,161
(WHIRRING RESUMES)

167
00:10:01,081 --> 00:10:03,001
NARDOLE: So, turn it and then it'll...

168
00:10:03,441 --> 00:10:05,161
DOCTOR: I'm turning it, help me.

169
00:10:32,561 --> 00:10:34,841
-You okay?
-Yeah, I'm fine.

170
00:10:40,041 --> 00:10:42,561
Sorry, can I ask?
What's that in your eye?

171
00:10:42,681 --> 00:10:44,801
It's just a defect in the iris.

172
00:10:45,041 --> 00:10:47,161
-Looks like a star.
-Well, it's a defect.

173
00:10:47,241 --> 00:10:48,681
At least,
it's a defect that looks like a star.

174
00:10:48,761 --> 00:10:50,081
I'm getting it fixed.

175
00:10:52,121 --> 00:10:53,441
Okay.

176
00:10:56,241 --> 00:10:57,721
Sorry, none of my business,

177
00:10:57,921 --> 00:11:00,561
but are you freaking out
about something?

178
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:06,881
Please, you can say no.

179
00:11:07,241 --> 00:11:08,761
Would you come with me,

180
00:11:08,881 --> 00:11:10,161
can I show you something?

181
00:11:10,281 --> 00:11:11,281
God, yes!

182
00:11:13,841 --> 00:11:15,561
BILL: I love this place, don't you?

183
00:11:15,841 --> 00:11:17,681
-HEATHER: I hate it.
-Why?

184
00:11:17,761 --> 00:11:19,441
I don't know, I just do.

185
00:11:20,001 --> 00:11:21,881
Everywhere I go, I just wanna leave.

186
00:11:22,801 --> 00:11:23,801
Can I come, too?

187
00:11:25,481 --> 00:11:26,481
Maybe.

188
00:11:39,041 --> 00:11:40,441
There's a puddle over there.

189
00:11:41,241 --> 00:11:43,001
It hasn't rained for a week.

190
00:11:43,321 --> 00:11:46,641
Yeah, but... Well, you know,
half the students here are blokes.

191
00:11:46,881 --> 00:11:48,041
Go and look in it.

192
00:11:48,401 --> 00:11:50,321
-You want me to look in a puddle?
-Please.

193
00:11:59,241 --> 00:12:00,521
Okay, I'm lookin'.

194
00:12:01,961 --> 00:12:04,081
-What am I lookin' at?
-Your reflection.

195
00:12:04,481 --> 00:12:05,841
(WATER SLOSHING)

196
00:12:06,321 --> 00:12:07,361
Yep, there it is.

197
00:12:08,161 --> 00:12:09,401
HEATHER: Did you see
what's wrong with it?

198
00:12:09,601 --> 00:12:11,841
My name's Bill, by the way.

199
00:12:11,961 --> 00:12:12,961
I'm Heather.

200
00:12:13,601 --> 00:12:14,681
Can you see what's wrong?

201
00:12:15,481 --> 00:12:16,961
Nothing, just looks like me.

202
00:12:19,721 --> 00:12:21,881
Oh! What is that?

203
00:12:24,441 --> 00:12:26,281
That's me, that's my face but

204
00:12:26,681 --> 00:12:28,041
it's wrong.

205
00:12:30,721 --> 00:12:31,721
Hey!

206
00:12:32,041 --> 00:12:33,841
Sorry, some other time.

207
00:12:35,601 --> 00:12:36,601
Promise?

208
00:12:41,561 --> 00:12:44,041
MAN: (WHISPERING) Pilot is located.

209
00:12:45,721 --> 00:12:48,561
Link is established.

210
00:12:50,281 --> 00:12:52,921
(CAROLLERS SINGING)

211
00:13:09,521 --> 00:13:10,521
DOCTOR: It's a rug.

212
00:13:12,081 --> 00:13:13,241
Haven't got you anything.

213
00:13:13,881 --> 00:13:14,881
It's okay.

214
00:13:14,961 --> 00:13:15,961
It was cheap.

215
00:13:24,041 --> 00:13:25,361
Going anywhere for Christmas?

216
00:13:25,721 --> 00:13:27,441
(CHUCKLES) I never go anywhere.

217
00:13:27,521 --> 00:13:28,681
That's not true.

218
00:13:29,321 --> 00:13:30,801
You go places, I can tell.

219
00:13:31,681 --> 00:13:33,081
My mum always said, "With some people,

220
00:13:33,161 --> 00:13:34,801
"you can smell the wind
in their clothes".

221
00:13:35,281 --> 00:13:36,321
Hmm?

222
00:13:36,681 --> 00:13:37,681
She sounds...

223
00:13:38,921 --> 00:13:39,921
Nice.

224
00:13:40,681 --> 00:13:41,881
She died when I was a baby.

225
00:13:42,241 --> 00:13:43,921
-Oh.
-Yeah.

226
00:13:47,441 --> 00:13:50,041
If she died when you were a baby,
when did she say that?

227
00:13:51,041 --> 00:13:52,281
In my head.

228
00:13:54,401 --> 00:13:57,281
Yeah, I'm supposed to look like her,
but I don't really know.

229
00:13:58,161 --> 00:14:00,321
There's hardly any photographs.

230
00:14:00,401 --> 00:14:02,401
She hated having her picture taken.

231
00:14:03,681 --> 00:14:06,481
But if someone's gone,
do pictures really help?

232
00:14:10,761 --> 00:14:13,401
I thought you'd enjoy choosing
something for yourself,

233
00:14:13,601 --> 00:14:15,201
as you're always passing judgements.

234
00:14:17,521 --> 00:14:19,241
I hope you didn't spend
too much on this.

235
00:14:19,681 --> 00:14:21,201
Nah, this should cover it.

236
00:14:21,801 --> 00:14:22,801
What's that?

237
00:14:23,241 --> 00:14:26,401
Oh, I found that in the back of a
cupboard, with all your old stuff.

238
00:14:27,001 --> 00:14:29,081
Just photographs, of your mum.

239
00:14:29,601 --> 00:14:30,761
I didn't know we had 'em.

240
00:14:50,721 --> 00:14:51,761
(SNIFFLES)

241
00:15:19,121 --> 00:15:20,121
Happy new term!

242
00:15:21,001 --> 00:15:22,201
With you in a moment.

243
00:15:27,921 --> 00:15:30,001
You said you needed
a crane to lift your box.

244
00:15:30,361 --> 00:15:31,961
DOCTOR: Sorry, what did you say?

245
00:15:59,441 --> 00:16:00,441
Hey!

246
00:16:03,401 --> 00:16:04,961
Still making eyes at a puddle?

247
00:16:06,641 --> 00:16:08,681
Did you ever work out what
was wrong with your reflection?

248
00:16:09,281 --> 00:16:10,361
Nah.

249
00:16:10,921 --> 00:16:13,041
Come around, I'll show you.

250
00:16:13,841 --> 00:16:15,361
Promise you won't go.

251
00:16:16,441 --> 00:16:17,561
Promise.

252
00:16:38,001 --> 00:16:39,001
Okay.

253
00:16:39,841 --> 00:16:41,281
Yeah, no worries.

254
00:16:43,441 --> 00:16:45,561
MAN: (WHISPERING) Pilot confirmed,

255
00:16:45,641 --> 00:16:48,081
pilot engaged.

256
00:16:52,041 --> 00:16:53,721
(DOOR CLOSES)

257
00:16:58,321 --> 00:16:59,321
What's wrong?

258
00:17:01,641 --> 00:17:03,081
She said it was a defect.

259
00:17:03,521 --> 00:17:06,441
But, what kind of a defect
puts a star in your eye?

260
00:17:07,561 --> 00:17:10,241
But that doesn't even matter
because she was right.

261
00:17:11,241 --> 00:17:13,281
There was something wrong when
you looked in the puddle.

262
00:17:14,881 --> 00:17:16,401
That was definitely my face.

263
00:17:16,801 --> 00:17:18,361
I see my face all the time.

264
00:17:18,721 --> 00:17:20,441
I never liked it,
it's all over the place.

265
00:17:20,521 --> 00:17:23,161
It's always doing expressions when
I'm trying to be enigmatic

266
00:17:23,241 --> 00:17:24,361
I know my face.

267
00:17:25,241 --> 00:17:27,281
And there was something wrong
with my face in the puddle.

268
00:17:29,801 --> 00:17:31,521
What could be wrong with your own face?

269
00:17:44,721 --> 00:17:45,721
Doctor!

270
00:17:50,641 --> 00:17:51,641
Doctor!

271
00:18:00,321 --> 00:18:01,321
(PANTING)

272
00:18:01,401 --> 00:18:03,161
-Why did you run like that?
-Like what?

273
00:18:03,281 --> 00:18:05,321
Like a penguin, with his arse on fire.

274
00:18:05,721 --> 00:18:06,721
Ergonomics.

275
00:18:07,721 --> 00:18:09,321
That's my face, yeah?

276
00:18:09,641 --> 00:18:10,841
I see you're a bit flexible
on the subject.

277
00:18:10,961 --> 00:18:11,961
Oh, you've no idea.

278
00:18:12,761 --> 00:18:14,721
Maybe it's got to do with
that thing in her eye.

279
00:18:14,801 --> 00:18:16,281
-How?
-Maybe she's like,

280
00:18:16,361 --> 00:18:17,681
affected by something.

281
00:18:17,761 --> 00:18:19,761
-By what?
-I don't know.

282
00:18:19,841 --> 00:18:23,081
Look, I know you know lots of stuff
about, well, basically everything,

283
00:18:23,241 --> 00:18:24,241
but do you know any sci-fi?

284
00:18:30,561 --> 00:18:31,641
-Go on.
-Well,

285
00:18:32,161 --> 00:18:34,161
what if she's possessed?

286
00:18:34,441 --> 00:18:35,481
Something like that?

287
00:18:36,121 --> 00:18:37,201
Possessed by what?

288
00:18:37,561 --> 00:18:38,681
I don't know.

289
00:18:39,801 --> 00:18:42,841
Saw this thing on Netflix,
lizards in people's brains.

290
00:18:43,921 --> 00:18:46,241
Right, so you meet a girl
with a discoloured iris,

291
00:18:46,361 --> 00:18:47,521
and your first thought is,

292
00:18:47,641 --> 00:18:48,761
she might have a lizard in her brain?

293
00:18:49,721 --> 00:18:51,601
I can see I'm gonna have to up my game.

294
00:18:54,841 --> 00:18:55,881
Oh!

295
00:18:56,201 --> 00:18:57,281
-What?
-Oh!

296
00:18:57,801 --> 00:19:00,081
-What is it, what?
-Oh, I get it.

297
00:19:00,281 --> 00:19:01,281
I see it.

298
00:19:01,921 --> 00:19:03,401
It was easy for you friend,

299
00:19:03,481 --> 00:19:04,481
because of her eye.

300
00:19:04,561 --> 00:19:05,961
What? Because it gives her
special powers?

301
00:19:06,041 --> 00:19:07,121
No!

302
00:19:07,441 --> 00:19:09,801
Because her face
isn't symmetrical, look.

303
00:19:11,601 --> 00:19:13,641
Look into the puddle.

304
00:19:14,081 --> 00:19:15,801
Your face looks wrong,

305
00:19:16,161 --> 00:19:17,321
because it looks right.

306
00:19:17,441 --> 00:19:20,281
What's the one thing you never see when
you're looking in a reflection?

307
00:19:20,721 --> 00:19:23,681
Your face. You never see
your face the right way around.

308
00:19:25,201 --> 00:19:28,201
Right, look for a freckle
or a funny tooth,

309
00:19:28,281 --> 00:19:30,201
-something that's not...
-My badge!

310
00:19:30,281 --> 00:19:33,521
See, your friend saw it straight
away because of her eye. (CHUCKLES)

311
00:19:33,761 --> 00:19:35,961
But that means we're like, a reflection.

312
00:19:43,681 --> 00:19:45,481
It's not

313
00:19:45,561 --> 00:19:46,561
reflecting you,

314
00:19:46,721 --> 00:19:47,721
it's mimicking you.

315
00:19:49,601 --> 00:19:51,601
There's something in the water,
pretending to be you.

316
00:19:54,281 --> 00:19:55,281
Of course,

317
00:19:56,721 --> 00:19:57,721
it isn't water.

318
00:19:59,441 --> 00:20:00,721
Now, what are these?

319
00:20:00,801 --> 00:20:01,881
Let's have a look.

320
00:20:01,961 --> 00:20:03,201
BILL: What are they?

321
00:20:04,641 --> 00:20:05,761
Scorch marks.

322
00:20:07,001 --> 00:20:08,001
Interesting.

323
00:20:15,161 --> 00:20:16,161
Right, you!

324
00:20:18,641 --> 00:20:19,641
Let's get you on the bus.

325
00:20:19,721 --> 00:20:20,721
The what? The bus?

326
00:20:20,801 --> 00:20:22,441
Tutorial's over, take the night off.

327
00:20:22,521 --> 00:20:23,521
It's all cancelled.

328
00:20:23,641 --> 00:20:25,441
Go and be a proper student.

329
00:20:25,521 --> 00:20:27,801
Text, snogging, a vegan wrap.

330
00:20:27,921 --> 00:20:29,281
But what about the puddle?

331
00:20:29,361 --> 00:20:33,561
Oh, it's just some freak optical effect.
I'm bored already.

332
00:20:35,401 --> 00:20:39,961
MAN: (WHISPERING) Passenger selected,
pursuit engaged.

333
00:20:50,961 --> 00:20:52,081
(WATER RUNNING)

334
00:20:54,881 --> 00:20:57,521
Hey, I'll make you a cuppa for the bath.

335
00:21:08,161 --> 00:21:09,841
(MOBILE RINGING)

336
00:21:13,761 --> 00:21:14,761
Hey.

337
00:21:15,041 --> 00:21:16,321
MOIRA: Sorry, I'm not there, love.

338
00:21:16,641 --> 00:21:19,321
But I think we both know,
it's time I treated myself.

339
00:21:19,961 --> 00:21:21,201
Are you with Neville?

340
00:21:21,281 --> 00:21:24,401
MOIRA: Why would I be back with Neville,
after last time?

341
00:21:24,721 --> 00:21:26,641
Why do you think I'm such an idiot?

342
00:21:27,321 --> 00:21:28,681
Well, you're calling from his phone.

343
00:21:31,721 --> 00:21:33,721
Is there someone staying here
in the flat?

344
00:21:34,441 --> 00:21:36,681
MOIRA: Of course not. No.
What are you talking about?

345
00:21:37,801 --> 00:21:41,361
Nothing, never mind.
I'll see you tomorrow.

346
00:21:42,641 --> 00:21:43,881
(WATER STOPS RUNNING)

347
00:21:53,401 --> 00:21:55,521
(WATER SLOSHING)

348
00:21:58,361 --> 00:21:59,361
Hello?

349
00:22:02,681 --> 00:22:04,081
Is someone in there?

350
00:22:05,801 --> 00:22:06,921
Is that Barry?

351
00:22:07,641 --> 00:22:10,121
Because she's with Neville,
and it's not my fault.

352
00:22:20,121 --> 00:22:21,641
Sorry, I need to know who's in there.

353
00:22:25,001 --> 00:22:26,081
I'm coming in.

354
00:22:26,681 --> 00:22:27,721
Do you hear me?

355
00:22:31,761 --> 00:22:33,761
Make yourself decent.

356
00:22:58,241 --> 00:22:59,441
(STAMMERING) If that's Barry,

357
00:22:59,521 --> 00:23:01,921
let's not make this worse,
just say it's you.

358
00:23:29,681 --> 00:23:30,801
(SHRIEKS)

359
00:23:44,201 --> 00:23:45,201
MAN: Hey!

360
00:23:50,681 --> 00:23:52,241
(PANTING)

361
00:23:58,641 --> 00:24:00,241
(WATER DRIPPING)

362
00:24:27,361 --> 00:24:28,361
Hello.

363
00:24:29,201 --> 00:24:30,321
Hello.

364
00:24:36,521 --> 00:24:37,521
You scared me.

365
00:24:38,041 --> 00:24:39,041
You scared me.

366
00:25:13,161 --> 00:25:14,201
You're dead.

367
00:25:14,641 --> 00:25:15,921
You're dead.

368
00:25:24,561 --> 00:25:25,761
(PANTING)

369
00:25:31,321 --> 00:25:32,401
Hello, Bill.

370
00:25:33,641 --> 00:25:34,881
Oh...

371
00:25:34,961 --> 00:25:36,801
(WATER SLOSHING)

372
00:25:38,961 --> 00:25:40,001
What's that?

373
00:25:48,081 --> 00:25:49,401
I'll tell you what it isn't.

374
00:25:50,121 --> 00:25:51,601
It isn't a freak optical effect.

375
00:26:01,121 --> 00:26:03,001
And it's following me.

376
00:26:03,761 --> 00:26:04,801
(BILL WHIMPERS)

377
00:26:10,841 --> 00:26:12,241
No. No. What are you doing?

378
00:26:14,321 --> 00:26:17,281
I'll tell you what,
let's just pop into my box.

379
00:26:17,361 --> 00:26:20,161
Your box? What good
is getting in your box going to do?

380
00:26:20,641 --> 00:26:23,161
What an extraordinarily long
and involved answer this is going to be.

381
00:26:26,601 --> 00:26:27,641
How do we stop her getting in?

382
00:26:27,721 --> 00:26:29,841
-We're trapped in here.
-Nothing gets through these doors.

383
00:26:30,601 --> 00:26:35,001
But they're made of wood.
They've got windows! (SIGHS)

384
00:26:39,401 --> 00:26:42,681
Look. This is all mad, I know, but...

385
00:26:42,761 --> 00:26:44,921
That's the girl I told you about.
Heather.

386
00:26:46,201 --> 00:26:48,761
Only, I don't think it's really her.

387
00:26:50,841 --> 00:26:54,681
I know this is hard to believe. I know
you're not exactly a sci-fi person...

388
00:26:58,441 --> 00:27:01,241
Time and Relative Dimension in Space.

389
00:27:03,721 --> 00:27:05,881
TARDIS for short.

390
00:27:08,961 --> 00:27:10,561
You're safe in here.

391
00:27:10,641 --> 00:27:12,601
You're safe in here
and you always will be.

392
00:27:20,161 --> 00:27:21,201
Any questions?

393
00:27:25,321 --> 00:27:26,841
Is this a knock through?

394
00:27:26,921 --> 00:27:29,281
(CHUCKLES) Well, in a way, yes.

395
00:27:31,921 --> 00:27:32,961
Look at this place.

396
00:27:35,961 --> 00:27:37,041
-It's like a...
-Spaceship.

397
00:27:37,121 --> 00:27:39,161
-Kitchen.
-A what?

398
00:27:39,441 --> 00:27:40,961
A really posh kitchen. All metal.

399
00:27:41,041 --> 00:27:44,041
What happened to the doors though?
Did you run out of money?

400
00:27:44,121 --> 00:27:48,081
What you are standing in
is a technological marvel.

401
00:27:48,561 --> 00:27:51,081
It is science beyond magic.

402
00:27:52,721 --> 00:27:55,121
This is the gateway
to everything that ever was.

403
00:27:56,321 --> 00:27:57,721
Whatever can be.

404
00:27:59,961 --> 00:28:01,321
Can I use the toilet?

405
00:28:03,001 --> 00:28:06,681
-Pardon?
-I've had a fright. I need the toilet.

406
00:28:07,201 --> 00:28:11,121
It's down there. First right, second
left, past the macaroon dispenser.

407
00:28:11,201 --> 00:28:13,761
-Thanks.
-Oh! Human.

408
00:28:14,401 --> 00:28:16,241
Human alert.
Do you want me to repel her?

409
00:28:16,321 --> 00:28:18,321
She's just passing through.
She wants to use the toilet.

410
00:28:18,401 --> 00:28:20,721
Oh. I'd give it a minute if I were you.

411
00:28:20,801 --> 00:28:23,001
-(THUNDERING)
-Oh! What's that?

412
00:28:23,081 --> 00:28:27,361
We have a encroacher on campus.
Extra-terrestrial. We're under attack.

413
00:28:29,401 --> 00:28:30,481
-Let's move.
-(GRUNTS)

414
00:28:32,801 --> 00:28:33,961
Oh, my God!

415
00:28:34,561 --> 00:28:37,081
-This isn't just a room, is it?
-No, it's not just a room.

416
00:28:38,161 --> 00:28:39,201
This is a lift!

417
00:28:45,001 --> 00:28:46,081
Well, come on.

418
00:28:55,601 --> 00:28:58,161
(BEEPING)

419
00:28:58,361 --> 00:29:01,001
No interference here as far
as I can see. Vault secure.

420
00:29:03,401 --> 00:29:04,921
So, your box can move?

421
00:29:06,281 --> 00:29:07,321
It can go anywhere it likes.

422
00:29:08,001 --> 00:29:09,601
Mmm. Good, innit?

423
00:29:10,201 --> 00:29:11,881
Anywhere at all in the whole university?

424
00:29:11,961 --> 00:29:15,441
Is it my imagination or is this
taking longer than normal?

425
00:29:18,281 --> 00:29:22,521
Hang on.
The room's still inside the box.

426
00:29:23,481 --> 00:29:25,241
-This isn't a knock through.
-No.

427
00:29:25,761 --> 00:29:28,761
Doctor, it's bigger on the inside
than it is on the outside.

428
00:29:28,841 --> 00:29:30,521
Hey, hey! We got there.

429
00:29:32,761 --> 00:29:34,641
How is that possible?
How do you do that?

430
00:29:35,721 --> 00:29:41,561
Well first, you have to imagine a very
big box fitting inside a very small box.

431
00:29:42,241 --> 00:29:45,241
-Okay.
-Then, you have to make one.

432
00:29:46,081 --> 00:29:47,881
It's the second part
people normally get stuck on.

433
00:29:48,121 --> 00:29:49,801
DOCTOR: Can we shut up, please.
Busy, busy.

434
00:29:49,881 --> 00:29:53,361
I need to know if there's any interest
in what's inside this vault.

435
00:29:53,441 --> 00:29:55,001
BILL: Why? What's inside it?

436
00:29:55,081 --> 00:29:57,201
Something I don't want anyone
being too curious about.

437
00:29:57,681 --> 00:29:59,321
So you put it
in the middle of a university?

438
00:29:59,401 --> 00:30:02,881
Oh, valid point. Yeah. Nice.

439
00:30:03,721 --> 00:30:06,161
Either the creature came here
specifically for what's in here

440
00:30:06,241 --> 00:30:07,441
or it's just a coincidence.

441
00:30:07,521 --> 00:30:10,441
-Just a coincidence.
-Well, we can't know that for sure.

442
00:30:10,961 --> 00:30:12,001
Yeah, we can.

443
00:30:12,961 --> 00:30:14,481
It was here for ages
before it did anything.

444
00:30:14,601 --> 00:30:16,681
If it had work to do,
why would it lie around in a puddle?

445
00:30:16,761 --> 00:30:18,241
I don't know. Maybe it's a student.

446
00:30:18,681 --> 00:30:22,161
(LAUGHS) Oh. Banter. It's good, this.

447
00:30:23,601 --> 00:30:24,641
Your go again.

448
00:30:25,521 --> 00:30:26,841
(WATER RUSHING)

449
00:30:32,081 --> 00:30:33,161
Nardole...

450
00:30:33,281 --> 00:30:34,761
(WATER DRIPPING)

451
00:30:35,681 --> 00:30:39,961
We need to move away from the doors
and towards the TARDIS.

452
00:31:14,281 --> 00:31:15,481
What if it attacks us?

453
00:31:18,201 --> 00:31:19,721
Well that's good news.

454
00:31:20,561 --> 00:31:22,921
It means it's not interested
in what's inside the vault,

455
00:31:23,401 --> 00:31:24,601
it just wants to kill us.

456
00:31:25,281 --> 00:31:26,321
Oh.

457
00:31:32,281 --> 00:31:33,601
-Run!
- (SHRIEKS)

458
00:31:35,041 --> 00:31:37,761
It's not interested in the vault.
It's chasing us.

459
00:31:38,161 --> 00:31:41,401
Let's give it a proper challenge.
Let's see how far she's prepared to go.

460
00:31:42,401 --> 00:31:43,721
What about my friend?

461
00:31:43,801 --> 00:31:45,481
What about Heather? Can you save her?

462
00:31:47,281 --> 00:31:50,081
First things first.
Let's see if we can survive her.

463
00:31:54,841 --> 00:31:56,881
-(BIRDS CALLING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

464
00:32:13,161 --> 00:32:15,361
-But...
-Yes.

465
00:32:15,921 --> 00:32:17,761
-We've moved again.
-We have.

466
00:32:19,441 --> 00:32:20,801
-It was night...
-Yep.

467
00:32:20,881 --> 00:32:24,241
Now it's day.

468
00:32:25,081 --> 00:32:26,121
Definitely day.

469
00:32:27,041 --> 00:32:29,921
-My God. We travelled in time?
-No, of course not.

470
00:32:30,281 --> 00:32:31,921
We've travelled to Australia!

471
00:32:37,881 --> 00:32:39,721
(PANTING)

472
00:32:44,561 --> 00:32:46,601
-How are you doing?
-How do you think?

473
00:32:52,641 --> 00:32:54,161
Right. Um...

474
00:32:56,281 --> 00:32:57,361
How do I help?

475
00:32:58,441 --> 00:33:00,241
-Can I ask you a personal question?
-No.

476
00:33:00,321 --> 00:33:02,841
-Can I anyway?
-Yes.

477
00:33:03,281 --> 00:33:05,561
-Are you from space?
-No, of course not.

478
00:33:07,081 --> 00:33:10,481
Nobody's from space.
I'm from a planet like everybody else.

479
00:33:10,561 --> 00:33:11,561
This planet?

480
00:33:13,601 --> 00:33:15,121
No, not specifically this one.

481
00:33:15,201 --> 00:33:17,081
Doesn't make sense then.

482
00:33:17,921 --> 00:33:19,721
-What doesn't?
-TARDIS.

483
00:33:20,321 --> 00:33:23,281
If you're from another planet,
why would you name your box in English?

484
00:33:23,361 --> 00:33:25,561
Those initials wouldn't work
in any other language!

485
00:33:25,641 --> 00:33:28,281
-People don't generally bring that up.
-It looks a phone box.

486
00:33:28,361 --> 00:33:31,841
Yes. Well, that's the cloaking device.
It sort of hides itself.

487
00:33:32,441 --> 00:33:34,601
It's hidden itself as box
with "Pull to enter” on the front.

488
00:33:35,241 --> 00:33:38,721
Uh-huh, it's stuck. It's supposed
10 blend in but it's broken.

489
00:33:40,561 --> 00:33:41,881
(LAUGHS)

490
00:33:42,761 --> 00:33:44,041
(WATER SLOSHING)

491
00:33:49,201 --> 00:33:50,241
Doctor...

492
00:33:51,921 --> 00:33:54,401
Out! Out! Everybody out! Shark attack.

493
00:33:54,481 --> 00:33:56,121
- (SHRIEKS)
-(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

494
00:34:00,481 --> 00:34:02,561
-Where are we going?
-As far as we can.

495
00:34:02,681 --> 00:34:06,041
She made Australia in a minute.
Let's see what she can really do.

496
00:34:06,121 --> 00:34:08,321
Sir, we're leaving Earth.
What about the vault?

497
00:34:08,441 --> 00:34:11,801
Oh, we're fine. If there's any trouble,
I'll get a message on this.

498
00:34:11,881 --> 00:34:13,721
Let's see how long
it takes her to get here.

499
00:34:14,881 --> 00:34:15,921
Where are we?

500
00:34:17,241 --> 00:34:18,721
Other end of the universe.

501
00:34:20,041 --> 00:34:24,921
23 million years in the future.

502
00:34:27,801 --> 00:34:29,921
Oh yes, it's a time machine, too.

503
00:34:53,321 --> 00:34:55,881
So, this is somewhere else.

504
00:34:55,961 --> 00:34:59,201
This is a different planet.
Not Earth, a different one.

505
00:34:59,761 --> 00:35:01,041
That's the general idea.

506
00:35:05,161 --> 00:35:07,601
That's different sky.
Is it made of something different?

507
00:35:07,681 --> 00:35:08,761
What is sky made of?

508
00:35:08,841 --> 00:35:10,521
-Lemon drops.
-(CHUCKLES) Really?

509
00:35:10,601 --> 00:35:11,841
No. But wouldn't that be nice.

510
00:35:12,321 --> 00:35:14,281
You can be very silly sometimes.
Do you know that?

511
00:35:15,401 --> 00:35:19,721
So, how do we know
this water thing is actually dangerous?

512
00:35:19,801 --> 00:35:22,641
-Because most things are.
-Hmm. That's true.

513
00:35:22,721 --> 00:35:25,281
-Why? Is everything out here evil?
-Hardly anything is evil.

514
00:35:25,641 --> 00:35:27,121
But most things are hungry.

515
00:35:27,561 --> 00:35:29,641
Hunger looks very like evil
from the wrong end of the cutlery.

516
00:35:29,721 --> 00:35:32,001
Or do you think that
your bacon sandwich loves you back?

517
00:35:32,801 --> 00:35:35,441
So what is it?
And what was it doing on Earth?

518
00:35:35,521 --> 00:35:39,001
Well, there were scorch marks
on the concrete where we found it,

519
00:35:39,561 --> 00:35:41,801
could have been left by a shuttle craft.

520
00:35:42,961 --> 00:35:44,561
The puddle, what did it look like?

521
00:35:44,681 --> 00:35:46,561
I mean, if that was a car
what would you say that was?

522
00:35:47,561 --> 00:35:49,041
(STAMMERS) An oil leak?

523
00:35:50,281 --> 00:35:52,081
So it's space engine oil.

524
00:35:52,161 --> 00:35:55,161
Intelligent oil.
Super intelligent space oil.

525
00:35:55,241 --> 00:35:57,001
No! Part of the ship itself.

526
00:35:57,081 --> 00:35:59,561
Shape-shifting fluid
that becomes anything it needs to be.

527
00:36:00,601 --> 00:36:01,641
Oh, seriously?

528
00:36:01,721 --> 00:36:04,481
DOCTOR: But it spent ages laying
around being a puddle. What changed?

529
00:36:04,681 --> 00:36:08,881
Your friend. She looked into it,
didn't she? More than once.

530
00:36:08,961 --> 00:36:10,001
So?

531
00:36:10,761 --> 00:36:13,041
Maybe it saw something it needed.

532
00:36:13,121 --> 00:36:16,681
What was she like, your friend?
What did she want? What did she need.

533
00:36:17,841 --> 00:36:19,281
Everywhere I go, I just wanna leave.

534
00:36:23,241 --> 00:36:24,481
I think she wanted to leave.

535
00:36:25,401 --> 00:36:26,481
See.

536
00:36:27,441 --> 00:36:29,561
The puddle found a passenger.

537
00:36:29,841 --> 00:36:35,561
A left-behind droplet of a liquid
spaceship. Single tear drop.

538
00:36:35,641 --> 00:36:37,241
Alone in a strange world.

539
00:36:37,321 --> 00:36:41,161
Then, one day it finds someone
who wants to fly away.

540
00:36:41,241 --> 00:36:43,241
Not just the passenger...
More than a passenger.

541
00:36:43,321 --> 00:36:45,881
It found a pilot so it ate her!

542
00:36:47,841 --> 00:36:49,841
So, why is it chasing this one?

543
00:36:49,921 --> 00:36:53,161
-Everything wants, everything needs.
-But why does it want her?

544
00:36:53,241 --> 00:36:55,961
I don't know.
I don't know everything, Nardole.

545
00:36:56,041 --> 00:36:57,641
I don't have it all written down.

546
00:36:57,721 --> 00:36:59,001
NARDOLE: You act like you do.

547
00:36:59,081 --> 00:37:00,841
DOCTOR: I act like I do
because I don't.

548
00:37:00,921 --> 00:37:02,881
NARDOLE: It must be looking
for something.

549
00:37:02,961 --> 00:37:04,561
DOCTOR: Of course it is.
Everything is.

550
00:37:04,641 --> 00:37:05,681
NARDOLE: But what?

551
00:37:05,761 --> 00:37:09,281
DOCTOR: What, in the end,
are any of us looking for?

552
00:37:09,361 --> 00:37:12,681
We're looking for someone
who's looking for us.

553
00:37:14,481 --> 00:37:16,521
Hey! Still making eyes at a puddle?

554
00:37:19,961 --> 00:37:21,561
- (SHRIEKS)
-Bill!

555
00:37:22,841 --> 00:37:23,841
Bill.

556
00:37:25,241 --> 00:37:26,601
(SHRIEKING)

557
00:37:27,081 --> 00:37:28,201
DOCTOR: Back to the TARDIS.

558
00:37:33,081 --> 00:37:34,121
(COUGHS)

559
00:37:34,601 --> 00:37:38,641
Okay. It's fast, it time travels
and never gives up.

560
00:37:40,401 --> 00:37:41,441
Plan!

561
00:37:42,161 --> 00:37:43,241
Basic sterilization.

562
00:37:43,321 --> 00:37:45,881
We're going to run that thing through
the deadliest fire in the universe.

563
00:37:45,961 --> 00:37:48,041
Yes! That sounds excellent.

564
00:37:48,121 --> 00:37:51,401
"The deadliest fire in the universe.”
That's definitely good.

565
00:37:51,481 --> 00:37:53,161
-How do we do that?
-The only way we can,

566
00:37:53,241 --> 00:37:55,441
-we run through it first.
-Less good now.

567
00:37:55,521 --> 00:37:57,641
-(THUNDERING)
-(GRUNTS)

568
00:37:57,721 --> 00:38:00,961
No, not there. I don't like it there!

569
00:38:03,481 --> 00:38:05,561
-Nardole!
-I don't like there.

570
00:38:08,601 --> 00:38:10,921
I want you running interference,
can you do that?

571
00:38:11,001 --> 00:38:12,441
-Can I say no, sir?
-No!

572
00:38:12,521 --> 00:38:13,961
-Yes, then.
-Thank you.

573
00:38:14,041 --> 00:38:15,081
But no, really.

574
00:38:15,161 --> 00:38:16,161
Where are we?

575
00:38:16,241 --> 00:38:18,041
Well, we're basically
in the middle of a war.

576
00:38:18,121 --> 00:38:22,801
No, but... It's a war zone.
And this is just your basic skirmish.

577
00:38:22,881 --> 00:38:24,961
And it's not as bad as it sounds,
I promise you.

578
00:38:25,041 --> 00:38:27,641
Come on. I've got friends here.
Old friends.

579
00:38:29,281 --> 00:38:30,521
I say friends...

580
00:38:30,921 --> 00:38:33,041
DALEK: The Doctor is detected.

581
00:38:33,521 --> 00:38:35,881
-Seek. Locate. Destroy.
-(MOANS)

582
00:38:37,881 --> 00:38:38,881
(GASPS)

583
00:38:39,481 --> 00:38:42,961
-Are we still in the future?
-No. This is the past.

584
00:38:43,441 --> 00:38:44,961
Doesn't look like the past.

585
00:38:47,201 --> 00:38:49,681
-Are we safe here?
-Well, that's up to Nardole.

586
00:38:49,761 --> 00:38:50,761
So probably not.

587
00:38:52,121 --> 00:38:53,281
Oh.

588
00:38:54,001 --> 00:38:56,281
Oh... Oh!

589
00:38:58,121 --> 00:38:59,641
NARDOLE: Keep moving, Doctor.

590
00:38:59,721 --> 00:39:02,241
-BILL: Where are going?
-Into the fire. Come on.

591
00:39:05,881 --> 00:39:08,201
(DISTANT SCREAMING)

592
00:39:10,361 --> 00:39:12,961
-MAN: Move! Move! Move!
-(SCREAMING)

593
00:39:13,041 --> 00:39:14,041
Who are those guys?

594
00:39:17,041 --> 00:39:19,281
Never mind them.
It's who they're firing at.

595
00:39:21,561 --> 00:39:22,841
(SCREAMING)

596
00:39:27,441 --> 00:39:29,201
(WATER RUSHING)

597
00:39:32,841 --> 00:39:33,881
Come on.

598
00:39:36,161 --> 00:39:38,001
-(BOTH PANTING)
-BILL: What's that?

599
00:39:38,081 --> 00:39:39,881
DOCTOR: The deadliest fire
in the universe.

600
00:39:39,961 --> 00:39:43,561
DALEK: Identify, intruder. Identify.

601
00:39:44,441 --> 00:39:46,201
Scan this device and identify me.

602
00:39:46,281 --> 00:39:49,081
DALEK: You are the Doctor.
You are an enemy of the Daleks!

603
00:39:49,401 --> 00:39:50,521
Oh, yes I am.

604
00:39:50,601 --> 00:39:52,121
DALEK: Exterminate!

605
00:39:54,241 --> 00:39:55,841
Exterminate.

606
00:39:56,361 --> 00:39:57,881
DALEK: Exterminate.

607
00:39:59,121 --> 00:40:00,561
Exterminate.

608
00:40:03,401 --> 00:40:04,801
-DALEK: Exterminate.
-(SCREAMS)

609
00:40:10,481 --> 00:40:11,721
-What was that thing?
-A Dalek.

610
00:40:11,801 --> 00:40:13,721
-A what?
-A Dalek.

611
00:40:13,801 --> 00:40:15,001
What's a Dalek?

612
00:40:15,081 --> 00:40:16,761
Never mind. It's a Dalek.

613
00:40:17,681 --> 00:40:19,041
DALEK: Exterminate!

614
00:40:21,241 --> 00:40:22,321
(BOTH GASP)

615
00:40:26,841 --> 00:40:29,801
DALEK: (DISTORTED) Exterminate...

616
00:40:30,041 --> 00:40:33,801
DOCTOR: That's wrong.
I know my Daleks and that's wrong.

617
00:40:37,681 --> 00:40:38,921
Oh, I see.

618
00:40:40,121 --> 00:40:41,361
You see what?

619
00:40:41,441 --> 00:40:43,961
I've sealed the area.
All the Daleks are quarantined.

620
00:40:44,041 --> 00:40:45,041
Except that one!

621
00:40:45,681 --> 00:40:48,361
It's okay, this isn't a Dalek. Look.

622
00:40:49,801 --> 00:40:50,961
Look at the eye.

623
00:40:51,841 --> 00:40:52,881
Heather.

624
00:41:11,681 --> 00:41:13,561
-Heather.
-DOCTOR: Interesting.

625
00:41:13,641 --> 00:41:16,161
You had a gun but you didn't use it.
Why?

626
00:41:16,241 --> 00:41:18,561
You've already taken one person
from Earth.

627
00:41:19,241 --> 00:41:24,081
I'm gonna let that pass because I have
to, but I will not let you take another.

628
00:41:25,761 --> 00:41:26,841
Go.

629
00:41:29,161 --> 00:41:30,841
Just go now. Fly away.

630
00:41:36,921 --> 00:41:38,241
Why won't you just go?

631
00:41:46,121 --> 00:41:48,761
-Promise you won't go.
-Promise.

632
00:41:50,241 --> 00:41:51,481
Oh, my God.

633
00:41:52,081 --> 00:41:53,241
I understand.

634
00:41:53,721 --> 00:41:54,841
You what?

635
00:41:54,921 --> 00:41:56,041
The last thing she said to me.

636
00:41:56,121 --> 00:41:57,801
She promised she wouldn't
leave without me.

637
00:41:58,201 --> 00:42:01,801
Her last conscious thought,
driving her across the universe.

638
00:42:01,961 --> 00:42:05,721
-Never underestimate a crush.
-(LAUGHS) You don't have to tell me.

639
00:42:05,961 --> 00:42:08,761
-What do we do?
-I don't know.

640
00:42:10,081 --> 00:42:13,521
She's not chasing you,
she's inviting you.

641
00:42:14,241 --> 00:42:17,961
Release her.
Release her from her promise.

642
00:42:28,361 --> 00:42:29,361
You have to let me go.

643
00:42:30,521 --> 00:42:32,001
You have to let me go.

644
00:42:33,361 --> 00:42:34,441
I will.

645
00:42:35,001 --> 00:42:36,121
I will.

646
00:42:43,641 --> 00:42:45,121
I really liked you.

647
00:42:46,041 --> 00:42:47,561
I really liked you.

648
00:42:47,721 --> 00:42:49,201
(WATER DRIPPING)

649
00:42:56,801 --> 00:42:57,841
DOCTOR: Bill.

650
00:42:59,401 --> 00:43:00,641
Don't! Don't!

651
00:43:01,561 --> 00:43:06,001
Don't do that. Listen.
Please, just listen to him.

652
00:43:09,041 --> 00:43:11,041
Don't! Don't! Bill, let go!

653
00:43:13,401 --> 00:43:14,521
DOCTOR: Bill listen to me.

654
00:43:15,041 --> 00:43:17,801
Whatever she's showing you,
whatever she's letting you see,

655
00:43:17,881 --> 00:43:19,121
it's a lure.

656
00:43:19,481 --> 00:43:22,921
It's a trap.
She's making you part of her,

657
00:43:23,001 --> 00:43:24,641
and you can never come back.

658
00:43:24,961 --> 00:43:26,641
HEATHER: 7 see what you see.

659
00:43:28,641 --> 00:43:30,481
BILL: It's beautiful.

660
00:43:31,041 --> 00:43:32,881
Bill, let go! You have to let go!

661
00:43:33,801 --> 00:43:35,721
DOCTOR: She is not human any more.

662
00:43:38,481 --> 00:43:40,161
Goodbye, Heather.

663
00:43:42,721 --> 00:43:45,161
Good bye, Bill.

664
00:43:47,161 --> 00:43:48,481
-Whoa!
-(PANTING)

665
00:43:49,721 --> 00:43:51,121
Bill. Bill!

666
00:44:01,161 --> 00:44:02,201
Are you all right?

667
00:44:04,561 --> 00:44:05,801
Yeah, I think so.

668
00:44:14,561 --> 00:44:15,961
You don't look all right.

669
00:44:16,241 --> 00:44:17,321
She's fine.

670
00:44:19,041 --> 00:44:21,001
That's the Doctor for you. (SIGHS)

671
00:44:21,641 --> 00:44:23,441
Never notices the tears.

672
00:44:31,401 --> 00:44:32,801
I don't think they're mine.

673
00:44:40,401 --> 00:44:41,401
(SIGHS)

674
00:44:42,361 --> 00:44:44,561
The vault alarm went off,
but it was nothing.

675
00:44:44,641 --> 00:44:47,881
A student was sick outside and it
registered as a biological attack.

676
00:44:47,961 --> 00:44:48,961
(LAUGHS)

677
00:44:50,441 --> 00:44:52,041
I saw it all for a moment.

678
00:44:53,441 --> 00:44:54,841
Everything out there.

679
00:44:55,081 --> 00:44:57,601
She was going to let me fly with her,
she was inviting me.

680
00:44:58,161 --> 00:45:00,361
-But I was too scared.
-Scared is good.

681
00:45:01,601 --> 00:45:04,561
Scared is rational.
She wasn't human any more.

682
00:45:04,921 --> 00:45:06,121
Will we see her again?

683
00:45:08,361 --> 00:45:09,521
Don't see how. (CHUCKLES)

684
00:45:15,681 --> 00:45:18,281
No, no, no, no, no.
You have to forget about that.

685
00:45:18,841 --> 00:45:20,081
I don't see how I can. (CHUCKLES)

686
00:45:21,361 --> 00:45:22,561
I do.

687
00:45:25,401 --> 00:45:26,841
Come here, Bill.

688
00:45:28,961 --> 00:45:30,121
What's up?

689
00:45:31,041 --> 00:45:33,761
-I just want to fix something...
-Whoa! What are you doing?

690
00:45:33,881 --> 00:45:36,521
-Don't worry, this won't hurt at all.
-No, but tell me.

691
00:45:36,801 --> 00:45:37,841
Nothing.

692
00:45:38,281 --> 00:45:40,401
Yeah. Because I think
you were going to wipe my memory.

693
00:45:42,401 --> 00:45:43,921
I'm not stupid, you know.

694
00:45:44,721 --> 00:45:45,721
What's the trouble with you?

695
00:45:45,801 --> 00:45:46,841
You don't think
anyone's ever seen a movie?

696
00:45:46,921 --> 00:45:48,841
I know what a mind-wipe looks like.

697
00:45:48,921 --> 00:45:50,881
I have no choice, I'm here for a reason.

698
00:45:50,961 --> 00:45:53,761
I am in disguise.
I have promises to keep.

699
00:45:54,401 --> 00:45:56,841
No one can know about me.

700
00:45:56,921 --> 00:46:00,121
This is the most exciting thing
that's ever happened to me in my life.

701
00:46:00,201 --> 00:46:02,641
-The only exciting thing.
-I'm sorry.

702
00:46:04,241 --> 00:46:06,201
(STUTTERS) Okay.
Let me remember just for a week.

703
00:46:06,281 --> 00:46:07,281
Just a week.

704
00:46:08,241 --> 00:46:10,241
Okay. Well, just for tonight.
Just one night.

705
00:46:10,521 --> 00:46:13,321
Come on, let me have
some good dreams for once.

706
00:46:16,841 --> 00:46:17,921
Okay.

707
00:46:20,721 --> 00:46:21,801
Do what you got to do.

708
00:46:24,721 --> 00:46:25,801
But imagine...

709
00:46:27,241 --> 00:46:30,561
Just imagine how it would feel
if someone did this to you.

710
00:46:46,441 --> 00:46:47,521
DOCTOR: Get out.

711
00:46:47,761 --> 00:46:49,001
-What?
-You can keep your memories.

712
00:46:49,081 --> 00:46:50,801
Now get out before I change my mind.

713
00:46:51,521 --> 00:46:54,401
Don't speak. Don't start.
Just run. Now. Go!

714
00:46:59,001 --> 00:47:00,281
(SIGHS)

715
00:47:02,921 --> 00:47:03,961
Shut up.

716
00:47:04,441 --> 00:47:05,921
You shut up as well.

717
00:47:08,521 --> 00:47:11,081
Will you all please just leave me alone.

718
00:47:11,161 --> 00:47:13,601
I can't do that any more, I promised.

719
00:47:16,241 --> 00:47:17,841
(PANTING)

720
00:47:40,241 --> 00:47:42,241
DOCTOR: It's a big universe...

721
00:47:42,721 --> 00:47:44,721
But maybe one day we'll find her.

722
00:47:54,121 --> 00:47:55,641
BILL: What changed your mind?

723
00:48:00,881 --> 00:48:01,961
Time.

724
00:48:04,081 --> 00:48:05,161
Time?

725
00:48:07,721 --> 00:48:09,721
And Relative Dimension in Space.

726
00:48:09,801 --> 00:48:10,841
(SNAPS FINGERS)

727
00:48:21,361 --> 00:48:22,641
It means...

728
00:48:23,601 --> 00:48:24,721
What the hell.

729
00:48:36,281 --> 00:48:38,001
DOCTOR: 7his is one
of the Earth's first colonies.

730
00:48:38,081 --> 00:48:41,001
-What are they, alien birds?
-DOCTOR: Tiny robots.

731
00:48:41,321 --> 00:48:42,681
That is a robot.

732
00:48:42,761 --> 00:48:43,921
He speaks emoji.

733
00:48:44,001 --> 00:48:45,601
Where are all the people?

734
00:48:46,001 --> 00:48:47,161
-BILL: Ah!
-(BUZZING)

735
00:48:47,281 --> 00:48:48,281
What, you're going back in?

736
00:48:48,361 --> 00:48:50,241
I'm having this really
childish impulse to blow it up.

737
00:48:55,841 --> 00:48:57,321
-You're the one who should be afraid.
-Never.

738
00:48:57,761 --> 00:48:58,801
DOCTOR: Get ready.

739
00:48:59,481 --> 00:49:00,641
-(SCREAMS)
-(ELECTRICTY CRACKLES)

740
00:49:00,761 --> 00:49:01,801
I'm the Doctor.

741
00:49:02,561 --> 00:49:05,961
I've been standing by the gates
of your world, keeping you all safe.

742
00:49:06,441 --> 00:49:07,641
I'm not stopping now.

743
00:49:07,721 --> 00:49:09,401
Any questions?

